<poem>
    <title poet="Bontemps_A">Southern Mansion</title>
<stanza>
<l n="1"><figLang form="simile">Poplars are standing there still as death </figLang></l>
<l n="2">And ghosts of dead men </l>
<l n="3">Meet their ladies walking </l>
<l n="4">Two by two beneath the shade </l>
<l n="5">And standing on the marble steps<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
</stanza>
<stanza>
<l n="6">There is a sound of music echoing </l>
<l n="7">Through the open door </l>
<l n="8">And in the field there is </l>
<l n="9">Another sound tinkling in the cotton<punc type="colon">:</punc> </l>
<l n="10">Chains of bondmen dragging on the ground<punc type="period">.</punc></l>
</stanza>
<stanza>
<l n="11">The years go back with an iron clank<punc type="comma">,</punc> </l>
<l n="12">A hand is on the gate<punc type="comma">,</punc> </l>
<l n="13"><figLang form="personification">A dry leaf trembles on the wall</figLang><punc type="period">.</punc> </l>
<l n="14">Ghosts are walking<punc type="period">.</punc> </l>
<l n="15">They have broken roses down </l>
<l n="16"><figLang form="simile">And poplars stand there still as death</figLang><punc type="period">.</punc></l>
</stanza>
</poem>
